KV.get handles response in callback.
If response has 403 status code (rpc error: rpc error: ACL not found) then we have ValueError: No JSON object could be decoded.

```python
 def callback(response):
                if response.code == 500:
                    raise ConsulException(response.body)
                elif response.code == 404:
                    data = None
               """Bug is here"""
                else:
                    data = json.loads(response.body)
                    if not keys:
                        for item in data:
                            if item.get('Value') is not None:
                                item['Value'] = base64.b64decode(item['Value'])
                        if not recurse:
                            data = data[0]
                return response.headers['X-Consul-Index'], data
```

Hello,

I have a trouble extending Smart Table with a new directive. I am currently working on a Plunk to share with you in order to reproduce the issue. Code is at http://embed.plnkr.co/qXr7vnS4qQw7CIOWIXTb/preview

At our company we wanted to extend Smart Table with a `st-url` directive in order to simplify AJAX loading of the collection in one attribute that handles filtering, sorting and pagination automagically

### The st-url directive
We designed such directive in order to be simplemost for every developer. Since in our company's projects we handle 90% the times paginated data tables with simple sorting, searching and inline-creation features, we preferred to wrap them into a single directive

    <table st-url="/path/to/controller" st-table="rowCollection">

The `st-url` directive, containing **only** the URL of the HTTP POST resource that returns the data, replaces the Smart Table's pipe function (the one you can override with st-pipe) in order to POST search, order and pagination data at once, and in order to retrieve the data collection from the server in order to be stored into the collection variable.

The client-server interface is fixed in the code, because this directive is born only to be used internally

Here is the code we wrote so far

	angular.module('smart-table').directive('stUrl', [ 'stConfig', '$timeout', '$log', '$http', function(config, $timeout, $log, $http) {
		return {
			require : 'stTable',
			controller : 'stTableController',
			scope : {
				stUrl : '@'
			},
			link : {

				pre : function(scope, element, attrs, ctrl) {
					var oriPipe = ctrl.pipe;
					var pipePromise = null;

					ctrl.preventPipeOnWatch();
					ctrl.pipe = function() {

						if (pipePromise !== null)
							$timeout.cancel(pipePromise)

						pipePromise = $timeout(function() {

							var tableState = ctrl.tableState();
							var pagination = tableState.pagination;
							var perPage = pagination.number || 10;
							var start = pagination.start || 0;
							// currentPage, perPage

							var order = tableState.sort;
							var filter = tableState.search.predicateObject;

							$http.post(scope.stUrl, {
								offset : start,
								perPage : perPage,
								sort : order,
								filter : filter
							}).then(function(result) {
								var response = result.data;
								// ctrl.displayedCollection = response.data;
								// scope.$parent.displaySetter(scope, response.data
								// || {});
								scope.rowCollection = response.data; //Don't know how to do

								tableState.pagination.numberOfPages = response.totalPages;
								oriPipe();

							});

						}, config.pipe.delay);

						return pipePromise;
					}

				},

				post : function(scope, element, attrs, ctrl) {
					ctrl.pipe();
				}
			}
		};
	} ]);


### The problem
After returning from the server, we must store the collection somewhere. Please ignore that we wrote `scope.rowCollection`, it was an attempt.

From the scope of the new pipe function we don't have means to store the result set to the object Smart Table uses as collection (the one declared in st-table).

- `scope.rowCollection` has two issues: it hardcodes member name and scope is **not** the controller scope (see Plunk)
- `displaySetter` is not accessible because it is not "publicly" declared in the Smart Table controller

## Wrapping it up
I would kindly ask if there is a way to programmatically set the Smart Table collection, **or** if this feature requires a slight edit in the code in order for Smart Table to expose the displaySetter function.

We have tried (and next message will contain a practical example) to edit Smart Table code by exposing a `setCollection` method in the `this` scope and succeeded in displaying the collection.

Thank you

