I have following snippet of code, which successfully compiles, but causes `arg(): could not convert default keyword argument into a Python object (type not registered yet?)`.
```
.def("build", [](Unitset& instance, UnitType type, Pybrood::UniversalPosition target) -> bool {
   return instance.build(type, TilePosition(target[0], target[1]));
}, py::arg("type"), py::arg("target") = py::cast(Pybrood::TilePositions::None))
```
No matter what I try here: `Pybrood::TilePositions::None`, `py::cast(Pybrood::TilePositions::None)`, `std::array<int, 2>(Pybrood::TilePositions::None)`, result is the same: compiles then fails in runtime.

`Pybrood::TilePositions::None` is `std::array<int, 2>` constant derived from another constant, not defined by me. That's why I want to preserve it as is.
```
typedef std::array<int, 2> UniversalPosition;
const UniversalPosition None = convert_position<BWAPI::TilePosition>(BWAPI::TilePositions::None);
```
I'm trying to replace custom position classes with simple std::array to get/pass python tuples "out of the box". I suspect this problem hides in some typeid magic, which doesn't allow typedef'ed things to be considered 'registered' without manual registering from scratch.

Please excuse my very shallow knowledge of C++ :fearful: How better could I deal with this problem?

HI,

In the handling errors section of https://docs.recurly.com/client-libraries/python it reads:

<code>
except ValidationError, errors:
  for e in errors.itervalues():
</code>

Which raises an error that errors has no itervalues.

I think it should read:

<code>
except recurly.ValidationError, vadlidation_error:
    for e in vadlidation_error.errors.itervalues():
</code>

~Victor

Hi, I am want to exploit the z3 solver's incremental solving to speed up my own constraints  solving. The question is the incremental solving can speed up the solving? For example, we have a lot of constraints. In order to explain the question, we use constraints1 and constraints2 to denote all of these constraints. We have 2 schemes to solve these constraints, as follow:

Scheme 1:
   context c;
   solver s(c);
   s.add(constraints1);
   s.check(); // assume return Sat.
   s.add(constraints2);
   s.check(); // assume return Sat.

Scheme 2:
   context c;
   solver s(c);
   s.add(constraints1);
   s.add(constraints2);
   s.check(); // assume return Sat.

I want to know the incremental solving used in Scheme 1 solving time less than Scheme 2? Does the z3 solver has this property? Actually I want to speed up the constraints solving. Thank you very much.

According to the Z3 Java API [documentation](http://z3prover.github.io/api/html/classcom_1_1microsoft_1_1z3_1_1_model.html#aceef5d8c0c6804f696668ac5cc48d850), if a constant does not have an interpretation in a model, `Model.getConstInterp(Expr)` should return `null`. However, I get an "invalid argument" `Z3Exception` on the latest master (0286cee45026a1cf97ae9f001b4049496267f691) build on Windows. This also holds for `Model.getConstInterp(FuncDecl)`. This behavior is reproducible with the following code.

```
Context context = new Context();
Solver solver = context.mkSimpleSolver();

BoolExpr a = context.mkBoolConst("a");
BoolExpr b = context.mkBoolConst("b");
BoolExpr expr = context.mkOr(a, b);

solver.add(expr);
solver.check();
Model model = solver.getModel();

System.out.println(model.getConstInterp(a)); // value of 'a' is 'true'
System.out.println(model.getConstInterp(b)); // Z3Exception: invalid argument
```

